<refnamediv><indexterm><primary sortas="create-http-health-checker">create-http-health-checker &mdash;
creates a health-checker for a specified load balancer configuration</primary>
</indexterm><indexterm><primary sortas="creates a health-checker for a specified load balancer configuration">
creates a health-checker for a specified load balancer configuration &mdash;
create-http-health-checker</primary></indexterm><refname>create-http-health-checker
</refname><refpurpose>creates a health-checker for a specified load balancer
configuration</refpurpose></refnamediv>
<refsynopsisdiv><title>&synp-tt;</title>
<cmdsynopsis><command>create-http-health-checker</command>&synopsis-common;
<arg><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;url <replaceable>"/"</replaceable></option></arg>
<arg><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;interval <replaceable>30</replaceable></option></arg>
<arg><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;timeout <replaceable>10</replaceable></option></arg>
<arg choice="opt">&Dash;&Dash;config <replaceable>config_name</replaceable></arg>
<arg choice="plain"><replaceable>target</replaceable></arg>
</cmdsynopsis></refsynopsisdiv>
<refsect1><title>&desc-tt;</title>
<para>This command creates a health checker for a specified load balancer
configuration. A health checker is unique for the combination of target and
load balancer configuration. </para>
<para>This command only works with the native load balancer provided with
the Sun Java System Application Server. It does not work with other load balancers.
</para>
</refsect1>
<refsect1><title>&opts-tt;</title>
<variablelist termlength="medium">&options-common;
<varlistentry><term><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;url</option></term>
<listitem><para>The URL to ping to determine whether the instance is healthy.
</para>
</listitem></varlistentry>
<varlistentry><term><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;interval</option></term>
<listitem><para>The interval in seconds the health checker waits between checks
of an unhealthy instance to see whether it has become healthy. The default
value is 30 seconds. A value of 0 disables the health checker.</para>
</listitem></varlistentry>
<varlistentry><term><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;timeout</option></term>
<listitem><para>The interval in seconds the health checker waits to receive
a response from an instance. If the health checker has not received a response
in this interval, the instance is considered unhealthy.</para>
</listitem></varlistentry>
<varlistentry><term><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;config</option></term>
<listitem><para>The load balancer configuration for which you create the health-checker.
If you do not specify a configuration, the command creates a health checker
for every load balancer configuration associated with the target. If no configuration
references the target, the command fails. </para><?Pub Caret1>
</listitem></varlistentry>
</variablelist></refsect1>
<refsect1><title>&oper-tt;</title>
<variablelist termlength="medium">
<varlistentry><term><replaceable>target</replaceable></term><listitem><para>
Specifies the target to which the health checker applies.</para>
<para>Valid values are:<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para><replaceable>cluster_name</replaceable>, which specifies the
health checker will monitor all instances in the cluster. </para>
</listitem>
<listitem><para><replaceable>stand-alone_instance_name</replaceable>, which
specifies that the health checker will monitor this stand-alone instance.
</para>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist></para>
</listitem></varlistentry>
</variablelist></refsect1>
<refsect1><title>&exam-tt;</title>
<example>
<title>Using the create-http-health-checker command</title>
<screen>asadmin> <userinput>create-http-health-checker --user admin 
--passwordfile password.txt --config mycluster-http-lb-config mycluster

</userinput>
Command create-http-health-checker executed successfully.</screen>
</example>
</refsect1>
